<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n11144b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n11" href="#n11144b">N11 (VI.B.5)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n11all.htm#n11144b"> 144(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> fishers hear rasps / empty skiffs</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Ce lieu abandonn&eacute; des humains, o&ugrave; la solitude de la terre se rencontre avec la solitude de l&apos;oc&eacute;an, est, selon d&apos;antiques l&eacute;gendes, le rendez-vous des &acirc;mes en peine. "Le peuple de ces c&ocirc;tes, dit le po&egrave;te Claudien, entend les g&eacute;missements des ombres volant avec un l&eacute;ger bruit. Il voit passer les p&acirc;les fant&ocirc;mes des morts.&rdquo; Selon Procope, <mark>les p&ecirc;cheurs entendent heurter &agrave; leur porte</mark> &agrave; minuit. Ils se l&egrave;vent er trouvent sur la plage des <mark>barques vides</mark> qui se chargent d&apos;h&ocirc;tes invisibles. <br>[This abandoned place of humans, where the loneliness of the earth meets with the solitude of the ocean, is, according to ancient legends, the rendezvous of souls in pain. &ldquo;The people of these coasts,&rdquo; said the poet Claudian, &ldquo;hear the groans of the shadows flying with a slight noise, and he sees the pale ghosts of the dead passing by.&rdquo; According to Procopius, the fishermen hear their door knocking at midnight. On the beach there are empty boats carrying invisible hosts. <small> &Eacute;douard Schur&eacute;, <a name="ESLG" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ESLG"><cite title="source">Les Grandes L&eacute;gendes de France</cite></a> (1921, 1892) 214-15</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
